annotation: Confirmed pure and stable based on NMR data
NMR spectrum is missing the aldehydic proton and the MW is not detected
No sample detected by NMR at T0
The originally declared Z-grades are inappropriate as the chemicals did not elute and were not detected.
There are a minimum of four species identified in the LCMS spectrum

The NMR spectrum has very little intensity suggesting absence of the chemical but volatilization is highly unlikely.It is possible that there is tautomeric exchange as 1,8,9-Trihydroxyanthracene (480-22-8) and Anthralin (1143-38-0) are tautomers of each other and it could lead to exchange broadening.
There is no evidence of what the impurities may be.

There are a minimum of four species identified in the LCMS spectrum but it is not clear whether this is degradation or not based on sample details. However, degradation/multiple species is obvious in some of the spectra.

Between T0 and T4 there is evidence of a chemical transformation and the suggestion is that full hydrolysis occurs as reported in https://www.jbc.org/article/S0021-9258(20)80284-1/fulltext and https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1536/
Loss in NMR intensity suggest physical loss of sample

The NMR spectra between T0 and T4 clearly shows degradation of the sample and is likely hydrolysis as reported previously: https://pubs.acs.org/doi/pdf/10.1021/jf60207a004.
